<header class="landing">
    <h1>ScadBundler <span class="live">Live</span></h1>
    <p class="tagline">Turn a multi-file OpenSCAD project into one file you can upload anywhere.</p>
    <p class="blurb">
        Parametric CAD lets you describe a model with code, so a single design can flex to any size or shape
        — but real projects split that code across many <code>.scad</code> files with <code>include</code>
        and <code>use</code>. Sites like Thingiverse, MakerWorld and Printables accept only a
        <strong>single file</strong>. ScadBundler Live inlines your whole dependency tree into one
        self-contained file. Drop your files below — everything runs in your browser, nothing is uploaded
        anywhere, and the result is byte-for-byte what the command-line bundler produces.
    </p>
    <p class="blurb">
        This page runs entirely in your browser via WebAssembly, which is great for small-to-medium
        projects but is inherently much slower than a native program — a large library-heavy project
        (think BOSL2-scale, a dozen+ files or several megabytes of source) that bundles in a couple of
        seconds on the CLI can take minutes here and feel a little frozen at times. It'll still get there,
        but if you have the technical means to run the
        <a href="https://github.com/Dano7/ScadBundler#readme" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
            command-line tool
        </a>, it'll be a much faster and smoother experience for bigger projects.
    </p>
</header>
